    category: ["social", "issue"],
    content: [
      "In a diverse world of many people coming together, nobody can live without social interactions.  From birth, we are welcomed by a particular group, to which we feel closely connected.  As our circles grow, we are exposed to various types of people, but we only tend to prefer to interact with the ones who are like-minded to us. Little by little, this kind of mindset becomes stronger and stronger to the point that we no longer feel the necessity in communicating with other people. As a consequence, the term clique was coined to describe a small group of people who spend their time together and do not welcome other people into the group. A relationship like this can be seen mostly among students because they are at an easy stage of being influenced by their surroundings, and they have a strong need to feel accepted and belonged. Whether voluntarily or involuntarily, we all get involved in some kind of cliques, and we, ourselves, as students can witness the presence of cliques in our classroom. Because of its noticeable impacts on the students both inside and outside the clique, we have decided to choose this matter as our main topic to conduct an attentive study on. In this paper, we will discuss the benefits, drawbacks, and related theories to cliques.",
      "Clique plays an important role in contributing not only to students’ in-class but also their out-class performance. The formation of cliques can be identified within different social environments and many significant factors throughout their lives, such as race, gender, religion, social status, social class, shared interests, and so on.  As expected, clique comes with both positive and negative effects; having a favorable group is essential for social upgrading, meaning that students can pursue and develop themselves by using the positive traits of other members in their clique as a reference group. Most importantly, it provides a sense of belonging, which can help them to figure out who they are and boost their self-confidence in trying new things, as they know that they are not alone. For instance, if one belongs to a group that is interested in studying, that individual will tend to imitate and conform to the habit of studying as well to be a part of that particular group. In addition to this, people in cliques are also free to express who they are, as they feel comfortable, warm, and without fear of being judged. However, in most cases, the disadvantages of cliques hold more power and effects than their benefits. Cliques can tear apart a lot of things in a matter of seconds, and this does not only happen to people outside the clique but to the insiders as well. For clique is seen as a brutal barrier to the outsiders as the whole group is not willing to accept others in. Because of this, students who do not belong in any cliques will feel lonely, and unwanted and find it hard to fit in. This is the main reason that leads to discrimination, which will create in-groups and out-groups. People tend to view the trait of their in-group as goodness, while the same trait is viewed as wrongness in the out-group. Besides this, the negative impacts of cliques do not only fall upon the outsiders but the insiders as well. Being in a certain type of clique sometimes takes away the chance from the students to be comfortable in their skin because they are afraid that they might no longer be able to stay in their clique. Furthermore, cliques rarely allow us to let new people join; as a result, this will affect your ability to change yourself and learn new things. Also, your communication skills will worsen. These are all the big issues that come alongside cliques.",
      "According to the functionalist perspective - which sees all parts of society working together to accomplish social harmony and social stability, clique is viewed as a prominent component that instructs individuals on how to work collaboratively and effectively in a society. Based on the same theory, cliques serve as a bridge to unite compatible people who can support one another and pursue activities that the members will all enjoy, which sometimes can contribute to social stability while sometimes can be disruptive to society. With the existence of cliques, people are also more likely to think alike and have the same perceptions toward their surroundings, and this is what leads to group-think. From the perspective of a functionalist, group-think allows the members belonging to the same clique to work together more effectively and more efficiently as everyone has the same goals. Conflict theorists, in contrast, believe that people at school are all different in various qualities such as attractiveness, fitness, and access to physical resources; hence, they fall into different areas of the spectrum of acceptability. Thus, the “superior” members of the school environment get together and oppress the “lesser” ones.",
      "To gain a better understanding of the topic above, our group has conducted a small and simple survey to our targeted audience who are students. We conducted this survey to enhance our level of understanding to a better degree of the topic at hand. Our group of six individuals slowly and deliberately formulated a questionnaire related to cliques and asked our chosen participants to give their honest opinions and perspectives on the formation of cliques whether they think of it as a good or bad thing. We have created nine questions that are complex yet simple enough for the average audience to understand. The questions that are included consist of opinion-based, multiple-choice questions that are based on general knowledge and our very own understanding. According to the results from this survey, eight out of ten people believe that everyone at school is in a particular clique. On the other hand, the remaining two agree with the idea that people can become friends with anyone and everyone, even if they are different from them. Based on the data, ten out of ten people think that cliques exist because people want to achieve a feeling of comfort, trust, and loyalty. Additionally, four candidates also state that another factor that leads to the form of cliques is avoiding isolation.  Moving on to another part, seven out of ten participants view that cliques can be both positive and negative, while the other three only see the dark side of cliques.",
      "Through our knowledge and the results from the conducted survey on the topic, it can be concluded that cliques can be both good and bad, and even though their drawbacks outweigh their benefits, sometimes it depends on us, ourselves to let how much of an impact clique has on our behaviors and perspectives toward in-class performance and classroom interactions.",
      "The world of cliques is very complicated and confusing. By being in one, students can be at an advantage or at risk of improving or disimproving themselves. Looking at it from a positive side, cliques give students a sense of belonging, confidence, and the potential to discover where they belong. However, from the opposite side, cliques can be hazardous as they limit creativity and diversity in friendships. It can be very difficult to not fall under a student clique but to avoid all those negative impacts, you have to be an open-minded person by trying to respect and understand other people; if every student practices this, the drawbacks of clique won’t be the most serious problem that affects their performance inside and also outside the classroom.",
    ],
