      "Every day, human actions have a significant impact on the environment. Through our actions, we are destroying habitats and endangering the lives of future generations. Nowadays, with the accelerated development of human civilization, we, mankind are introduced to new equipment and technology, resulting in a more sophisticated lifestyle. However, with more than 7.53 billion people on the planet, the earth will one day no longer withstand the drawbacks and pollution that humans have left behind. Moreover, with the unstoppable population growth of population day by day,  more trees have been cut down to make spaces and accommodation for the new generation. In addition, more population, also means more transportation needed, leaving an environmental footprint. According to an online news article in, Washington Post, developing countries are found to be more affected by pollution such as air pollution while developed countries are more healthy (Mooney, 2016). In this essay, we will discuss the comparison between the two countries which are Cambodia, a developing country, and Singapore, a developed country in three main areas related to their cases, effects, and solutions.",
      "Air pollution originated from the combustions in the transport, household, industrial, and energy sectors. Burning fuels releases air pollutants into the environment or atmosphere which dramatically affects the quality of air. According to Environment Performance Index, Cambodia, although it is not a developed and industrialized country, still ranked 164 out of 180 countries in 2018. In Cambodia, the transportation sector has the most serious effect on the quality of air as the number of vehicles and fuel consumption is increasing significantly. As reported by The Phnom Penh Post, in 2014, there were more than 3.2 million vehicles registered. Due to this enormous number of vehicles, it will produce a large amount of combustion which extremely pollutes the atmosphere. In this part, if we talk about the symbolic interactionism perspective, it means that people nowadays are addicted to a new culture that shows off their values and property. The riches, therefore, bought new cars to illustrate their property, and the people who live in the medium class attempt to buy new vehicles to not be looked down on as poor or lacking money by the surrounding people. Furthermore, hundreds of tuk-tuks and buses perpetually operating around the Angkor Wat area. The environment in Angkor Wat, and Siem Reap was at risk of damage from acid rain due to the great amount of fuel consumption. From a structural-functionalist perspective, it means that the results had been changing dramatically because of the needs of humans that they are trying to find a job in which income is acceptable and possible to support their families such as those who are driving tuk-tuks.",
      "Currently, many investors came to Cambodia to start their businesses due to cheap labor. Most of the investors are doing business with a factory that takes advantage of cheap labor to manufacture their products in Cambodia. As we can see that factories produce a very serious amount of combustion which extremely threatened the environment. Talking to conflict theory, the worker was exploited by the capitalists or investors and those workers had no choice but to work for those capitalists although they know that they are being exploited. If we reflex this on the environmental issues, because of the advantages that the investor wants to grasp, the atmosphere in Cambodia is indirectly polluted by their factory. As a result due to the diverse issues of air pollution mentioned above, the polluted air can harm the health of humans. It includes discomfort such as irritation to the human’s nose, throat, eyes, and skin. Moreover, it can also cause headaches, dizziness, and nausea. Besides, bad smells made by factories are also considered to be a factor that can harm human health as well even though the odors are less serious.",
      "Singapore is well known as one of the cleanest countries in the world. Trees are grown everywhere and according to research, it is estimated that there are approximately 7 million trees along the street as well as in the park. Moreover, every park is connected to a smart system that creates a clean green society. However, those trees cannot fully keep the air clean which leads Singapore to be faced with air pollution. Singapore first faces air pollution in 1984 due to the dramatic increase in pig farming. Pig farming seems to only affect both land and water pollution but the wastes and the feces that are left from the pig also harm air pollution since these liters potentially contain harmful substances like nitrate, phosphorus as well as bacteria. Because of these substances, many people’s respiratory systems are damaged which causes possible diseases such as heart and lung disease. As a result, this problem is completely solved by the Singapore government by reducing the farm from 200 pig farms which contain about 50000 pigs to 22 pig farms which contain only approximately 300000 pigs by 1990. Similarly, Singapore today still faces air pollution and the main source is not pig farming but the burning of fossil fuels for heat generation in industries, electricity generation, and transportation to meet citizen demand. As a result, those factories emit tons of smoke which creates a haze that affects Singapore’s air quality. Not only this, but this polluted haze also causes shortness of breath, asthma, respiratory irritation, and infections, and can even do permanent damage to lung tissue, which reduces their ability to absorb oxygen even during normal breathing. To minimize this polluted haze, Singapore’s government employs a strategy of encouraging citizens to use environmentally public transportation and electric vehicles. Moreover, reducing traffic congestion is also introduced to improve air quality in Singapore. Artificial intelligence and street cameras should be operated to ensure a smoother flow of traffic. These strategies can ensure that air quality remains good despite Singapore’s dense urban landscape and large industrial base.",
      "In comparison between the air pollution in Cambodia and Singapore, there are some interesting similarities and differences. Cambodia has is a less serious problem with air pollution since there was war and there were fewer factories than in Singapore. In the past, Singapore's air pollution was caused by pig farming, while Cambodia has not encountered serious air pollution yet. But later on, materialism took over Cambodian people's mindset which led to the usage of vehicles to show off their wealth and their power in the urbanizing society. The use of fossil fuels is a big factor in the pollution in both countries. Fossil fuel was the main power resource in the factories for industrial production. Both pollutions in these two countries have such a big impact on the health of living species in their respective country. For the solution to air pollution in Singapore, the government has two solid solutions such as encouraging Singaporeans to use public transportation that cuts down the high rates of traffic congestion and decreases the smoke coming out from vehicles. Adding an AI camera to the roads is also a good addition to the solution. Another solution is to reduce the use of fossil fuel as a power resource and replace it with electricity. Meanwhile, in Cambodia, the only solution from the government is using public transportation but it is not quite convenient because people still value materialism and continue to increase the number of vehicles in the country.",
      "In conclusion, for the past ten years, climate change has been a major and global problem that cannot be neglected and the increase of carbon dioxide is rapidly growing. Some of the highly suggested solutions are to reduce the use of private vehicles and more public transportation such as public buses and metro for a faster commuting experience. Furthermore, we can also conclude that the government alone cannot tackle all of these problems at once without the help of all citizens too.",
